    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2044680923" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2044680923" />
    <a title="Cornerofmadness" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2832635-cornerofmadness"><img alt="Cornerofmadness" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1272143226p2/2832635.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2044680923?book_show_action=true">Jun 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cornerofmadness" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cornerofmadness" href="/user/show/2832635-cornerofmadness">Cornerofmadness</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2832635-cornerofmadness?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2832635-cornerofmadness?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2044680923&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2044680923" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer639729968798104512">I found this Brother Cadfael in an old box and couldn’t remember rereading it. Growing up in the 80s, this was one of my favorite series. Cadfael holds a special place in my heart. It’s amazing though how styles have changed over the decades. This was less than 160 pages and the word perspicacity appears in the blurb (I doubt we’d see much of that these days). But to be honest I’m hoping this was merely a less than stellar volume because I wouldn’t mind rereading the series (and I’m always afrai</span>
  <span id="freeText639729968798104512" style="display:none">I found this Brother Cadfael in an old box and couldn’t remember rereading it. Growing up in the 80s, this was one of my favorite series. Cadfael holds a special place in my heart. It’s amazing though how styles have changed over the decades. This was less than 160 pages and the word perspicacity appears in the blurb (I doubt we’d see much of that these days). But to be honest I’m hoping this was merely a less than stellar volume because I wouldn’t mind rereading the series (and I’m always afraid to reread the faves of my youth because far too often it’s like ‘wow, what was I thinking’).<br /><br />If I read this (and I think maybe I had) almost none of it stuck with me. As a historical story, this is good with the exception of a rather slow beginning. As a mystery, it’s poor. In fact, Cadfael is a secondary character in many ways in this one and there really isn’t a crime. The novel opens with the report of of one of Empress Maude’s men being killed after trying to get an important bishop to swing his support from King Stephen to Maude. Then this doesn’t get mentioned again until Olivier (a young knight) shows up to talk to Hugh (the sheriff) about finding a young man, Luc, who has run off and was the clerk and potential heir to the murdered man and then dropped again until the last couple of chapters. There’s no detecting, there’s no nothing as far as a mystery is concerned.<br /><br />Much of the story is about St. Winifred’s day, a Welsh saint associated with healing. Most of Cadfael’s scenes are his thoughts about where her bones truly are (and it’s not at his monastery though they think they are which happened in an earlier novel) and treating the wounded pilgrims to the site: especially two sets of pilgrims. There is Alice Weaver who has brought her nephew, Rhun, who has a shriveled, twisted painful leg and his sister, Melangell, with the hopes that Rhun will be cured. On the way Melangell has fallen in love with Matthew, a young educated man who is the companion to Ciaran, who claims to be dying and wants to get home to Wales, thinking Winifred won’t cure him. He has taken a strange vow to walk barefoot and wear a huge galling cross the whole way, something even the pious Cadfael thinks is strange and stupid.<br /><br />The pilgrims command a good deal of the scenes. There is a reliance on the unreliable narrator (which I don’t really like). As I said, as a mystery it fails but as a historical story, complete with the mystical, it is good. I am glad though that this wasn’t my first Cadfael read because I would have been much more disappointed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="639729968798104512" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


