    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3769335097" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3769335097" />
    <a title="Carl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6991135-carl"><img alt="Carl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1549577478p2/6991135.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3769335097?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carl" href="/user/show/6991135-carl">Carl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3769335097" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18286375101731737272">I love this old and true Peters Medieval Mystery series: The Chronicles of Brother Cadfael. The character of Cadfael himself is a Welsh Benedictine monk living at Shrewsbury Abbey, in western England, in the first half of the 12th century. The historically accurate stories are set between about 1135 and about 1145, during &quot;The Anarchy,&quot; the destructive contest for the crown of England between King Stephen and Empress Maud.<br/><br/>“The Pilgrim of Hate” is set during 1141. It is the fourth anniversary of </span>
  <span id="freeText18286375101731737272" style="display:none">I love this old and true Peters Medieval Mystery series: The Chronicles of Brother Cadfael. The character of Cadfael himself is a Welsh Benedictine monk living at Shrewsbury Abbey, in western England, in the first half of the 12th century. The historically accurate stories are set between about 1135 and about 1145, during "The Anarchy," the destructive contest for the crown of England between King Stephen and Empress Maud.<br /><br />“The Pilgrim of Hate” is set during 1141. It is the fourth anniversary of the transfer of Saint Winifred's bones to the Abbey at Shrewsbury; it is a time of celebration for the 12th-century pilgrims gathering from far and wide. However, in distant Winchester, however, a knight has been murdered. Perhaps he was a supporter of the Empress Maud, one of the pretenders to the throne?<br /><br />This was another very enjoyable instalment in the series. The story refers back to events in two previous Cadfael books which I enjoyed.<br />Peters has a good sense of time and place, as well as the religious order. Perhaps one of the better stories in the series, “The Pilgrim of Hate” is good due to exceptional characterization, including the return of a character from a previous book. As well, the plot was nicely planned, especially with some twists and surprises which kept the reader guessing. Very enjoyable and highly recommended series.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18286375101731737272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


