    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1917672355" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1917672355" />
    <a title="Lance" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46538050-lance"><img alt="Lance" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441159873p2/46538050.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1917672355?book_show_action=true">Feb 23, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lance" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lance" href="/user/show/46538050-lance">Lance</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=looking-for-clues">looking-for-clues</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1917672355" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1105116599556759903">&quot;<i>It was not one man&apos;s death, it was a bitter symbol of the abandonment of law and the rejection of hop and reconcilliation.</i>&quot;<br/><br/>In the tenth book of the <i>Brother Cadfael</i> series, Ellis Peters brings together many of the themes which have been slowly escalating through the earlier novels for a mid-point climax. The English civil war has taken a decisive turn, placing the cunning vindictive Empress Maud within a few months of coronation at King Stephen&apos;s expense. &quot;<i>A better general, that she is.</i>&quot; And the</span>
  <span id="freeText1105116599556759903" style="display:none">"<i>It was not one man's death, it was a bitter symbol of the abandonment of law and the rejection of hop and reconcilliation.</i>"<br /><br />In the tenth book of the <i>Brother Cadfael</i> series, Ellis Peters brings together many of the themes which have been slowly escalating through the earlier novels for a mid-point climax. The English civil war has taken a decisive turn, placing the cunning vindictive Empress Maud within a few months of coronation at King Stephen's expense. "<i>A better general, that she is.</i>" And the king's own half-brother, an oily politician revealed as a conniving man of the world rather than of God is behind it all. "<i>'When Bishop Henry of Blois shifts, all men shift with him, like starvelings huddled in one bed.</i>" Although everything looks decided at the outset in this book, the volatile personalities of those involved hint towards even more serious reverses to come. "<i>Put the crown in her hands and she may, not so much drop it, as hurl it at someone against whom she has a score to settle.</i>"<br />During Bishop Henry's own conference to smooth over his previous affiliation with his half-brother Stephen, a knight is murdered in the act of protecting a petitioner for King Stephen. Thus tragic event seems far off in time and place from Shrewsbury Abbey, but with the anniversary of Saint Winnifred's translation to the abbey fast approaching, Cadfael may find the mystery coming to him after all. "<i>'It grows customary to sigh and forget. At which, as I know, you are a very poor hand.</i>" <br />A strange pair of pilgrims, one who has mutilated his feet in a vow to travel barefoot to Wales, and a dark silent young man of the same age come to haunt the abbey during the celebrations. "<i>The barefoot traveller, and his keeper and worshipper.</i>" Cadfael is suspicious of the offering of self-inflicted pain where Ciaran could have been using his good health to help others. "<i>A strange piety it seems to me to take upon oneself ostentatious pain.</i>" But even he needs all not only his great detective skills but also his spiritual insights to separate between the two which is the murderer and which is the avenger.<br /><i>The Pilgrim of Hate</i> also sees a beautiful exploration of a number of Peters' minor themes. There is the teenage boy Rhun who has come from far south on the hopes of his family that his wasted lame leg will be cured when all he really wants is for them to be happy and free. Rhun's disability is treated sensitively and he is a complete complex human being both despite and because of it, a really heart-warming depiction. "<i>Cadfael saw that the boy was beautiful, the planes of his face as suave and graceful as any girl's, the curving of his fair hair round ears and cheeks angelically pure and chaste.</i>" Peters also explores the tragedy of forbidden love, "<i>They were pale as lillies, bright as stars, and solemn as the grave.</i>", and Cadfael's prayers to meet once more with his ellusive half-Syrian son are met with customary wit and whimsy, "<i>'By the grace of God and a goat-herd.'</i>"<br />Final words to Brother Adam of Reading:<br />"<i>'I suppose rogues will make their way everywhere, even among the saints.</i>"</span>
  <a data-text-id="1105116599556759903" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


